thread I recently came across a kind of deterrent ad from the western police district: "deprived of the right to have social media". the ad refers to a judgment from the bergen district court from this autumn, where such a loss of rights was sentenced indefinitely.

the man had committed serious sexual offenses. he was active in a sports environment where he came in contact with teenagers between 14 and 16 years. in a large number of cases he persuaded the offended to send him pictures of the genitals, and had physical intercourse with some of them.

the serious nature of the case is unquestionable. many will probably think that no punishment is severe enough and that the loss of rights is fully reasonable. who does not want to protect children from abusers? but when a person is more or less deprived of the right to be social in a digital arena forever,

we should stop and ask ourselves which legal society we want to live in. what rule of law values are we willing to sacrifice in the service of that good? and is the denial of the right to use social media at all an effective tool?

this man should not be able to have contact with family, friends and colleagues on skype or messenger, not receive invitations to events on facebook and not be able to follow the lives of his circle of friends on instagram. he is also cut off from a great deal of news, such as these

disseminated on social media with accompanying debate surfaces and other debate forums where he could develop himself as a thinking individual. in other words, the man is sentenced to live in a time that no longer exists.

now I hardly think that the loss of rights would have been maintained if the case had been appealed upwards in the system. the encroachment on freedom of expression and the right to normal life is too massive and confusing. moreover, it is highly doubtful whether the court had sufficient legal authority.

what does such a condemnation express? yes, it expresses that one gives up the belief in rehabilitation for certain criminals. The idea of rehabilitation has traditionally been strong in Norwegian criminal law, and is often used as an explanation for our low recidivism rates.

but when convicts are never allowed to return to a normal life, positive change is not facilitated. instead, convicts are defined as an eternal enemy of society. then one forgets that rehabilitation is also important to protect children from abuse.

even though the man has been sentenced to a loss of rights, there is still little that prevents him from actually creating new profiles, now under a pseudonym. therefore, the instrument is in any case hardly suitable for stopping a repeat offender. here, custody is a more suitable tool. It is also important to remember

that the problematic use of social media is in itself a criminal behavior that the police could intervene with by other means also in the future. in some such cases, however, it is the case that the person who is discovered becomes so ashamed that the desired individual preventive
effect has been achieved already during the investigation. the judgment from bergen district court is final.

we probably agree that family life does not start with "yes" in the church or at the courthouse, so why should it be the requirement to be reunited with the one you love most? why then is marriage certificate the requirement for entry for our foreign boyfriends?

6. why is it okay for jd to choose to set the limit for entry by marriage certificate and give a 30 hour deadline before closing the country? It takes a very long time to organize any kind of travel these days. p. a. book and take a test before departure, it takes a lot of time to organize.
